{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17505159","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17505159"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:26:57+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:26:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2413"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2413","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2413"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.2,0.74,0.03,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2413"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78912"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2413","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2413"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2413"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64261"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"593"},{"type":"tags","id":"1540"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1796"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1886"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8941"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8949"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78912","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78912"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 23-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with heavy vaginal bleeding and lower abdominal pain for the past four hours. She is eight weeks pregnant with her first pregnancy. She has no significant medical history and takes only pregnancy vitamins. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 115/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 99% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Abdominal examination reveals mild suprapubic tenderness. Speculum examination shows an open cervical os with products of conception visible. Bedside ultrasound confirms an inevitable miscarriage. After discussion of management options, the patient opts for medical management.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate single pharmacological agent for management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ergometrine","Mifepristone","Misoprostol","Oxytocin","Tranexamic acid"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with an inevitable miscarriage, characterised by an open cervical os with visible products of conception. After appropriate counselling about management options (expectant, medical, or surgical), she has chosen medical management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMisoprostol\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate single agent for medical management of miscarriage. It is a prostaglandin E1 analogue that causes strong myometrial contractions and cervical softening and dilation. It can be administered orally, sublingually, or vaginally, with success rates of 80-90% for complete evacuation of products of conception.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMifepristone\u003C/strong\u003E is a progesterone receptor antagonist primarily used in combination with misoprostol for medical termination of pregnancy. While it may be used \u0027off-label\u0027 in some settings for miscarriage management, it is not typically used as a single agent and is less effective than misoprostol alone for this indication.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EErgometrine\u003C/strong\u003E is an ergot alkaloid that causes uterine contractions. While it may be used in the management of postpartum haemorrhage, it is not indicated for management of miscarriage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOxytocin\u003C/strong\u003E stimulates uterine contractions and is used for induction of labour and management of the third stage of labour. It is not indicated for management of early pregnancy loss.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETranexamic acid\u003C/strong\u003E is an antifibrinolytic agent that may help reduce blood loss in heavy bleeding but does not assist with evacuation of products of conception. It may be used as an adjunct therapy but is not appropriate as primary management.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Misoprostol is the preferred single pharmacological agent for medical management of inevitable miscarriage.","Medical management of miscarriage is an appropriate option when there are no contraindications and the patient prefers this approach.","Patient choice between expectant, medical, and surgical management is important in miscarriage care."],"references":["Allen R, O\u0027Brien BM. Uses of misoprostol in obstetrics and gynecology. Rev Obstet Gynecol. 2009 Summer;2(3):159-68. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/19826573/","Chu JJ, Devall AJ, Beeson LE, Hardy P, Cheed V, Sun Y, et al. Mifepristone and misoprostol versus misoprostol alone for the management of missed miscarriage (MifeMiso): a randomised, double-blind, placebo-controlled trial. Lancet. 2020 Sep 12;396(10253):770-778. Available at: https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736(20)31788-8/fulltext","Krugh M, Maani CV. Misoprostol. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Updated 2020 Jul 10. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK539873/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64261"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2413"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64261","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64261"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-13T11:09:27+10:30"